Context("Matrix");
$microA1 = random(30,60);
$fridgeA1 = random(10,30);
$stoveA1 = random(20,50);
$microA2 = random(25,55);
$fridgeA2 = random(12,40);
$stoveA2 = random(15,45);

$microX1 = random(30,60);
$fridgeX1 = random(10,30);
$stoveX1 = random(20,50);
$microX2 = random(25,55);
$fridgeX2 = random(12,40);
$stoveX2 = random(15,45);

$Jan=Matrix([[$microA1,$fridgeA1,$stoveA1],[$microX1,$fridgeX1,$stoveX1]]);

$Feb=Matrix([[$microA2,$fridgeA2,$stoveA2],[$microX2,$fridgeX2,$stoveX2]]);

$JanplusFeb = $Jan+$Feb;

############################################################
# Body
############################################################

BEGIN_PGML
During the month of January, "ABC Appliances" sold [`[$microA1]`] microwaves, [`[$fridgeA1]`] refrigerators, and [`[$stoveA1]`] stoves, while "XYZ Appliances" sold [`[$microX1]`] microwaves, [`[$fridgeX1]`] refrigerators and [`[$stoveX1]`] stoves.

During the month of February, "ABC Appliances" sold [`[$microA2]`] microwaves, [`[$fridgeA2]`] refrigerators, and [`[$stoveA2]`] stoves, while "XYZ Appliances" sold [`[$microX2]`] microwaves, [`[$fridgeX2]`] refrigerators and [`[$stoveX2]`] stoves.

Write a [`2 \times 3 `] matrix summarizing the sales for the month of January. (Keep the order of information). [_]*{$Jan}{5}

Write a [`2 \times 3 `] matrix summarizing the sales for the month of February. (Keep the order of information). [_]*{$Feb}{5}

Using matrix addition, write a [`2 \times 3 `] matrix summarizing the total sales for the months of January and February. [_]*{$JanplusFeb}{5}

END_PGML

